ges and objects, from printed paper money, passports, and almanacs to temporary festival installations and relics of the demolished Bastille. Addressing this mass of images conventionally ignored in art history, The Politics of the Provisional contends that they were at the heart of debates on the nature of political authenticity and historical memory during the French Revolution. Thinking about material durability, this book suggests, was one of the key ways in which revolutionaries conceptualized duration, and it was crucial to how they imagined the Revolution’s transformative role in history.The Politics of the Provisional is the first book in the Art History Publication Initiative (AHPI), a collaborative grant from the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation. Thanks to the AHPI grant, this book is available on a variety of popular e-book platforms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aArt and popular culturezFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aArtxPolitical aspectszFrancexHistoryy18th century. 7aART / European.2bisacsh  aFrench Revolution.  aFrench Revolutionary festivals.  aP.-F. Palloy.  aP.-L. Debucourt.  aRepublican calendar.  aassignats.  aephemera.  amemory.  amoney.  amonument.  aprints.  aprovisionality.  atime.  atrauma.  atrompe-l’oeil.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271061900?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271061900423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271061900/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyt